                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18421128-250-offence-1 t18421128-name-1295"></join>John Moore</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1296" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1296" type="surname" value="MOORE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1296" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MOORE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a pawnbroker, and live at Woolwich. The prisoner was my warehouse-boy—Hunter, one of my men, brought me a bundle con<lb></lb>taining the articles produced, which are mine—I then asked the prisoner to</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184211280168"></xptr>
               <p>give me the key of his box—I and my young man examined his box, and in it were various things, and amongst them these twelve shirts, a remnant of cloth, a jacket and waistcoat—he said his mother had bought them in Rag<lb></lb>fair—I have not the slightest doubt that they are pledges, but I cannot swear to them—I can swear to these collars, and part of this satin.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you any personal knowledge on the subject? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not any—these collars appear to have been dirtied since they have been in my possession—they are quite new—only one has been worn—they do not bear any mark—I have a duplicate relating to these collars, which I found in the prisoner's pocket, for "12 collars, 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., 19th August, 1841," in the name of "Ann Thompson, Church-street"—this is my ticket of the articles—it is the one I kept—the customer is not here—it is the handwriting of one of my young men.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18421128-name-1297" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1297" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1297" type="surname" value="HUNTER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18421128-name-1297" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT HUNTER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the prosecutor's service. I took in these twelve collars—this duplicate is my writing, and ought to have been on these collars in the shop.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character; and a gentleman engaged to take him as an apprentice.)</p>
